Package: powerctl
Version: {{ VER }}
Architecture: all
Maintainer: Gabriel Guillou guillou.gabriel@gmail.com
Homepage: https://github.com/DaemonCores/DaemonCores-VE
Section: admin
Priority: optional
Depends: coreutils, util-linux, linux-perf, {{ DEPS }}
Recommends: hdparm
Description: measured performance-per-watt CPU operating-point controller
 A lightweight bash daemon that keeps the CPU at its measured efficiency knee
 and only spends frequency (and therefore watts, heat and fan noise) when a
 sustained load actually benefits from it.
 .
 It measures the real frequency/power curve of this machine with RAPL by
 sweeping the factory frequency steps under load, picks the knee as the default
 operating point via scaling_max_freq, and raises the cap toward the factory
 maximum only under sustained utilization. Everything stays inside the factory
 range, so there is no undervolt or overclock and no crash or corruption risk.
 .
 Calibration loads the CPU and therefore runs only in an idle window, or on
 demand with "powerctl --calibrate". Pairs with fanctl: less heat lets the fans
 run lower.
 .
 It also applies safe peripheral power management: SATA link power (low power
 between commands, instant wake), PCI runtime power management, optional PCIe
 ASPM, and optional idle-disk spin-down that always excludes ZFS-backed, mounted
 and root disks. Every knob auto-disables when the hardware does not support it.
